  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 자허자(子虛子) : '
    value: 실제로 없는 공상적(空想的)인 인물로 쓰는 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 고금이 …… 한 손가락이니 : '
    value: 공손용자(公孫龍子)에 있는 말인데, 흰말[白馬]과 말[馬]이 다르니 같으니 하던 끝에 붙은 말이다. 지(指)는 해석자에 따라 혹은 손가락이라 하고 혹은 가리키는 뜻이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 이것이 이른바 …… 막히지 않음이라 : '
    value: 이것은 《주역》의 태괘(泰卦)에서 나온 말인데, 음양이 조화되고 천하가 태평한 기상을 말한 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 과보(夸父) : '
    value: 걸음 잘 걷는 과보란 자가 해와 경주(競走)하다가 중도에서 목이 말라서 죽었다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 대완(大完) : '
    value: 한 무제(漢武帝)가 이광리(李廣利)를 시켜 군사를 거느리고 대완국(大完國)을 쳤다. 그것은 대완국에 준마(駿馬)가 많은 것을 탐낸 것이었다. 이겨서 준마는 많이 얻어 왔으나 군사가 많이 죽었고, 그 뒤에 대완이 여러 번 반란을 일으켰다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 도끼가 …… 창이 이지러질 : '
    value: 《시경》파부편(破斧篇)에 있는, 주공이 내란을 평정한 것을 옮은 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 선성(宣聖)도 살고자 하였다 : '
    value: 《논어》에, “공자가 구이(九夷)에 가서 살고 싶다.” 하였다는 말이 있는데, 옛 선비들이 그것을 우리나라에 해당된다 한 사람이 있다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 비간(比干)을 봉하고 : '
    value: 비간(比干)은 은나라의 포악한 임금 주(紂)에게 간(諫)하다가 죽임을 당한 사람인데, 주 무왕이 주를 쳐서 멸하자 비간의 무덤을 봉해 주었다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 정공(丁公)을 죽이고 : '
    value: 한 고제(漢高帝)가 처음에 항우의 장수 정공(丁公)에게 추격을 당하여 칼날이 거의 몸에 닿을 지경인 위급한 때에 고제가 정공을 돌아보면서, “두 어진 이가 서로 이렇게 화를 줄 것이 무엇입니까.” 하고 빌었더니, 정공은 그만 칼날을 거두었다. 그 뒤에 항우가 망하자 정공이 고제를 찾아 갔더니, 고제는 은혜 갚기는 고사하고 도리어 정공을 죽이면서, “남의 신하로서 불충(不忠)하여 항왕(項王)으로 하여금 망하게 한 것은 이놈이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 전대(專對) : '
    value: 외국에 나가서 전권으로 교섭한다는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 공자의 자리가 …… 탄식하네 : '
    value: 공자와 묵자 두 분은 세상을 구제하기 위하여 돌아다니기 때문에 앉은 자리가 따뜻할 겨를이 없고, 구들에 그을음이 타서 검게 될 겨를이 없었다는 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 昴 : '
    value: 昂
  - key: '[주-D002] 城 : '
    value: 域
  - key: '[주-D003] 水 : '
    value: 木
english:
  title: A Rhapsody on Clear Skies
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A rhapsody is the art of expounding and narrating events—a descendant of ancient poetry. When poetry cannot exhaust one's intent, a rhapsody is composed to complete the expression. When the Han Forest official Chen came on his embassy, following all he encountered, his words flowed forth in essays and verses, filling scrolls and rolls. Among these, he composed a rhapsody on clear skies—its prose flowing like water, undulating and profound, capturing what words alone could never fully convey. Its ultimate purpose is to trace the roads traveled, record observations of distant lands, celebrate fidelity to the royal mission, and rejoice in the completion of ritual ceremonies—a true flowering of literary grace and elegance. I, though unworthy, venture to follow his refined patterns and cobble together this humble offering for his instruction. Long ago, Zuo Tai-chong labored ten years composing his Rhapsody on the Three Capitals before finally completing it. My small learning and shallow experience have produced this hasty work—scarcely worthy of notice. Yet since the official Chen represents the Son of Heaven, charged with proclaiming imperial edicts, his joy in clear skies carries great weight. I, a humble man, gaze in reverence upon the boundless imperial grace, admire his virtue, marvel at his talent, and lament his departure, which none may prevent. Though our rhapsodies share the same intent, our choice of words differs. I humbly record this as a parting gift, hoping the official will forgive my audacious presumption.

    Now begins the verse:

    When the phoenix calendar marks the year and the azure dragon builds its position,
    Zi-xu met Wu-you, and together they ventured forth—
    Traversing a hundred ages in their wanderings,
    Circulating through the six realms,
    Making the cosmos itself their dwelling,
    The four seas their hunting grounds.
    They rode upon the infinite expanse, drifting and floating,
    Climbed Kunlun and raised their heads on high.
    The three luminaries revolved at their command,
    The distant lands of Ho and Yue lay within their fingertip's reach.

    Zi-xu then addressed Wu-you, saying:
    "Alas! Ancient and modern are but one steed,
    Heaven and earth but a single finger's point.
    Before the age of Pao-xi and the gap-toothed Zhuangzi,
    All is shrouded in obscurity.
    Yet from the Three August and Five Emperors onward,
    Records are complete.
    Some virtuous, some not—
    Who truly stands above, and who below?
    Heaven's heart is benevolent;
    Why should it slight one and favor another?
    And yet order does not remain order forever,
    Chaos does not forever remain chaos.
    All is tangled confusion without end.
    Who can pilot a light vessel upon the sea of letters,
    Drive the four steeds of the arts pavilion,
    Charging up and down, proclaiming all on my behalf,
    Leaving nothing undone?"

    Wu-you replied:
    "Ah! What you describe is like one who sees the finest hair
    Yet misses the cartload of firewood,
    Observes a small stone yet misses Mount Tai.
    Now our radiant empire
    Has fixed its throne at Yan and Yun,
    Controlling the strategic passes of Yu and Long,
    Its territory spanning ten thousand li,
    Flowing boundlessly in all directions,
    Reaching outward to the four seas.
    Resources abound, and the people rest in peace.
    The cold find warm garments, the hungry find full bellies.
    Whether traveling mountains or sleeping by waters,
    No barrier gates impede the way.
    This is what we call the great harmony of heaven and earth,
    When all things flourish without obstruction.

    Why consult dusty tomes and engage in empty discourse?
    Would it not be better to observe the present age and seek its truth?
    To gain faith not through direct sight
    But through true testimony to the ear?
    This is not like a rider wandering the great plains,
    Having nowhere to rest, yet wandering all the roads of the world."

    Hereupon Zi-xu smiled in agreement and sought to depart with Wu-you,
    Casting bones to divine the auspicious omen,
    And swift as lightning traversed the nine provinces.
    They paid homage at the hall of great rituals, journeying to the ten days.
    At first, gathering countless spirits in floating procession,
    Cloaking themselves in clouds and rainbows,
    When heaven's horses neighighed, the attendants sighed with melancholy.
    Gazing down, the three sacred mountains seemed but straw heaps,
    The Yellow River gleaming like a single thread of flow.
    They washed their hair in the Salty Pool,
    Dried it in the morning sun of Fusang.
    The heavens opened and closed, rising and falling,
    As the rain shower whispered sweetly to them:
    "If you would but cultivate beauty and embrace sincerity,
    Why flutter so high and empty,
    Bathing merely in fragrant waters?"

    Then, keeping measure to distant paths,
    Climbing steep heights and crossing treacherous peaks,
    They witnessed the splendid exploits of kings and hegemons past,
    Survey the wondrous marvels of the great capitals.
    Circling through Ji province with leisurely steps,
    Observing the land's auspicious terrain.
    Though mighty Kuafu pursued the sun with tireless stride,
    One could only perceive his weariness in mere moments.

    See how Yifu Mountain looms as guardian,
    How the Yellow River surges across the plain,
    How Juyong Pass stands firm with its burden,
    Thousand-mile torrents rushing forth—
    These are the secret recesses of heaven and earth,
    The very root of Yan and Zhao.

    Then Wu-you bowed low and sighed, looking up to lament:
    "Resplendent is our radiant empire!
    Responding to heaven, following human hearts,
    It fashions glorious achievements,
    Expands the imperial map,
    Examines the writings of ancient sage-kings,
    Establishes its capital here,
    Dwells in the center, governing all lands.
    Through all under heaven, to the furthest reaches,
    The multitudes press forward in respectful throngs,
    Converging upon the central plain.

    The excellence of institutions and culture—
    Flourishing and refined—
    Its heights without limit,
    Its density without gap.
    This is the convergence of a hundred kings' wisdom,
    Unchanging through ten thousand ages.
    As many streams flow to the sea,
    As sinews and vessels attach to the spine,
    Though the Five Emperors returned and the Three Kings rose anew,
    They could add nothing to this.
    Should they attempt to elaborate further,
    They could only repeat what is already achieved.

    Ritual and music shine with clarity; laws are firmly established;
    Benevolent models are displayed; grand strategies are set forth.
    Smoke and fire rise for ten thousand li; people and creatures multiply abundantly.
    The perfection of governance surpasses all antiquity.
    Swords are beaten into plowshares; wild peoples are transformed to peace.
    North and south sing one note; east and west follow one principle.
    Through interpreters and envoys bearing gifts,
    All come to the court to present their tribute.
    None but bow their heads in submission,
    Receiving our ordinances.
    From the red coral islands to the desert wastes,
    From exotic kingdoms to distant frontiers,
    All establish officials and divide responsibilities,
    Exposing their hearts as hands, following as feet.
    Even the tiniest insects, the slenderest grasses,
    Bask in dew and find their dwelling.
    The four seasons regulate heat and cold;
    Sun and moon illuminate dawn and dusk.

    Yet know this: when sage-kings of old held the great throne,
    They did not traffic in hollow words,
    But practiced virtue alone.
    When the people suffer heat, they refresh them with coolness;
    When the age grows dark, they show them bright skies.
    Thus the transforming grace of viewing all as one
    Knows no distinction between inner and outer.
    It must give abundantly and receive sparingly,
    Must rescue the poor and support the weak.
    Through this, the Way shines resplendent,
    The four seas find peace and prosperity.

    No need to exhaust the armies through endless campaigns,
    As Han Wu pursued conquest in the lands of Da-wan.
    No need to shatter axes and break spears,
    As the Duke of Zhou campaigned in mist and rain.
    I have heard: above and below work as one,
    Ruler and ministers complete each other.
    The Change says: 'Clouds follow the dragon, wind follows the tiger,
    Water flows where there is moisture, fire seeks the dry.'
    When the sage acts, ten thousand things are revealed.
    The response of vital force knows no barrier of form—
    This is nature itself, needing no artifice.

    Thus where there is a wise ruler above,
    Below there must be worthy princes.
    Year by year they bring their seasonal tributes,
    Coming to pay court.
    The emperor bestows upon them fragrant spirits,
    Displaying his favor.

    Behold this kingdom called Choson!
    The Bohai Sea stretches to the south;
    the Long White Mountain lies to the north,
    Extending over a thousand li,
    Mountains and rivers form its boundaries.
    Its wealth and military strength
    Lead all nations.
    Its customs honor propriety and righteousness;
    Its people are quick of eye and ear.
    Its rulers possess princely virtue;
    Its scholars embody scholarly conduct.
    Ranks and distinctions maintain the hierarchy;
    Harmony in musical tones accords the sounds.
    The walls stand firm as golden ramparts;
    The field divisions stretch without deviation.
    The simplicity of its people's hearts,
    The beauty of its transforming influence—
    This is where the Sage would wish to dwell,
    Where the Great Yu chose to remain.

    Consider how in the twilight of the former Koryo,
    When ruler was foolish and ministers cruel,
    When sin and villainy overflowed,
    When robbers and brigands roamed freely,
    Holding the throne like bristles on a hedgehog—
    Our Great Ancestor came forth.
    Through a hundred battles, he broke the siege,
    Like water pouring from an upturned vessel.
    The people found refuge and safe rest;
    The state's fortune did not tilt.

    Then, responding to heaven's mandate and following human desire,
    He transformed family into state;
    Four borders grew clear and peaceful.
    He elevated the worthy and capable,
    Dispelled the dim and deluded,
    Exalted the loyal and struck down the false,
    Raised exemplars and banished tyrants.
    He balanced the five elemental energies, gathered the three essences—
    Forced to nurture the people through benevolence,
    To move heaven through sincerity.

    As a tributary kingdom, he submitted to the celestial court,
    Requesting investiture from the imperial throne.
    The emperor rejoiced, marveled, and honored this.
    Generation after generation receiving imperial favor,
    Protecting the livelihood of the multitudes.
    Now the current king inherits the throne,
    Expressing loyalty ever more ardently.
    With each season's local products,
    Royal tributes are presented.
    Heaven's regard is known by virtue;
    Its bestowal flows in endless succession.

    Ah! Is this not the fortunate coincidence of great peace and auspicious governance?
    When the celestial envoy arrives,
    The king goes forth to receive him,
    Armed guards stand in solemn array,
    Painted halberds and engraved shields gleam bright.
    The imperial grace descends deep,
    Flowing like monsoon rains, like a vast ocean.
    The king bows in reverent submission,
    Feeling the divine authority most near.
    With utmost care he serves the superior;
    With utmost benevolence he reaches the distant.
    The imperial virtue spreads broad and wide,
    Like heaven and earth, vast and infinite.
    The king's sincere heart shines pure,
    Like sun and stars, luminous and clear.

    From this time forth, heaven's steps grow level, jade measures harmonize,
    Phoenixes sing on hills, unicorns appear in meadows,
    Accomplishing the splendid achievement of great peace and harmony.
    Just as a single hair falls to the blazing fire.

    Zi-xu then said:
    "You have truly understood the greatness of our radiant empire,
    And perceived the virtue and wisdom of the Eastern Kingdom's ruler.
    Yet heaven's way speaks not, and things flourish—
    Because the five elements' officers proclaim their vital force.
    The ruler speaks not, and the nations rest—
    Because his ministers of all powers proclaim his way.

    Take the Han Forest official Chen and the Grand Ritual Master Gao—
    Their literary beauty, their lofty integrity!
    Their characters refined as jade polished by great rivers,
    Clear as autumn sunshine.
    Their compositions ornate with every device,
    They are the pillars of the literary forest,
    The elder statesmen of the cultural realm.
    More than this—their every word and gesture follows rule and measure,
    All their actions accord with ritual and law.
    They are like phoenixes and sacred fungi growing in the great courtyard,
    Like auspicious stars and propitious clouds shining in clear skies.
    Why should they not compose the Hymn of Deer from thousand-li distances,
    And answer the summons to the nine-layered palace?

    In this age of cultural brilliance, with such worthy ministers,
    Bearing imperial edicts to distant shores,
    Their mission carries sovereign authority,
    Holding high the scepter of the imperial envoy,
    Transmitting the words of the Son of Heaven,
    Their voices shake mountains and valleys,
    Their presence turns heaven and earth.
    Is it not fitting that they spread the supreme benevolence and boundless grace
    Of the emperor throughout all the realm?

    When these two return to report their mission,
    Let the kingdom-ruler convey his heartfelt respect,
    Assuring no failure in his princely duties,
    So that the Eastern realm may forever receive the imperial grace,
    Extending to sons and grandsons,
    Continuing in endless succession
    Until ten thousand ages hence, transmitted forever."

    Wu-you replied: "It shall be so."
    Then they bowed to each other in mutual respect and deference.
    Now they must part; Confucius' mat grows cold,
    Mozi's hearthstone fails to darken with soot.
    The cloud-like procession prepares for departure,
    The heavenly steeds cry out to begin.
    Ancient cypress trees toss their beards,
    Mountains by the sea reveal their peaks.
    Dawn clouds trail like silk—
    Gazing after the dust of the departing train, one cannot overtake it,
    Only distant stones stand stark and towering.
  footnotes:
    - Zi-xu and Wu-you are fictional characters representing abstract philosophical perspectives, employed in the tradition of classical Chinese dialogues to explore complex ideas.
    - The 'three luminaries' refer to the sun, moon, and stars.
    - The reference to 'clear skies bringing joy' alludes to the Daoist concept of natural transformation and the harmony between human governance and celestial patterns.
    - Kuafu was a mythical giant who famously pursued the sun until he collapsed from exhaustion, here used as a metaphor for the difficulty of comprehending the vastness of the empire.
    - The 'Five Emperors' and 'Three Kings' are legendary sage-rulers of ancient China whose wisdom this poem suggests cannot be surpassed.
    - The allusion to 'sage-kings' and their practice of virtue rather than force references the Confucian ideal of benevolent governance.
    - Choson (Joseon) refers to the Korean kingdom to which this rhapsody is dedicated.
    - The 'Great Ancestor' refers to the founder of the Joseon dynasty.
    - The final image of Confucius' mat growing cold and Mozi's hearthstone failing to darken is a classical reference meaning these sage-wanderers had no rest from their labors to improve the world.
